comments.text:
To be fair, that is generalizing a whole lot. Sure, the field is slimmer in 
big broadcasting than on youtube, but there's still room for unique talent 
and creativity. All TV isn't cookie-cutter Hollywood bullshit. HBO and BBC 
has both shown that, just to mention two.

On the other side of the coin, you'd be hard-pressed to make any sort of 
living off of youtube unless you have some kind of unique talent. Saying 
that anyone can do it, or rather that anyone can do anything and be 
successful, is overstating it, by a pretty large margin. Even PewDiePie, 
who at a cursory glance only seems to spend his videos screaming and having 
tourettes-fits in swedish at video games, has a certain je-ne-sais-quoi 
that many a rage-gamer have tried to replicate, and mostly failed 
miserably, while he rakes in the views by the boatload. You need talent and 
above that commitment to succeed at anything.

Additionally, I'd argue that comparing TV and Youtube is comparing apples 
and oranges. They are completely different beasts, in short. I suppose you 
could compare youtube to news programming, talk shows and the lot, but I 
don't expect that we'll see big budget dramas produced primarily for 
youtube for a very long time. That's just not what youtube is about.
